## Getting started

1. Navigate to the [MARIA webpage](https://cs6440-s18-prj44.apps.hdap.gatech.edu/).
2. After the login prompt appears, click OK.

## User profiles

1. Stay on the **Physician** tab and notice the &#39;user account&#39; and &#39;user balance&#39; representing your Ethereum account address and the associated Ether balance.
    1. Your balance is denominated in Wei.
    2. User balance is provided by truffle in our private blockchain

## Host a competition

### Adding data

1. Before hosting a competition, you&#39;ll need to add some data.  For purposes of this proof-of-concept application, we found a good dataset online from the National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases that contains 768 patient records. The objective of the data set is to diagnostically predict whether or not a patient has diabetes mellitus, based on certain diagnostic measurements included in the dataset.  We performed exploratory data analysis on the competition data set.  Some of the key findings from the set we used include:
    1. Diabetes patients on average have higher BMI
    2. Diabetes patients on average have higher Glucose concentration in glucose tolerance test
    3. Diabetes patients on average have higher triceps skin thickness
2. To divide the data into training and testing data, we used sklearn&#39;s train\_test\_split. We used this library to slice the data set to 2/3 training, 1/3 testing.  The training set with classification labels were provided to the competition participants, while a test set without labels was given to the participants for generating testing outcomes.

While data wrangling is outside the scope of this application, we suggest completing an exploratory data analysis on the data set you chose to use for your competition.  You want to be able to:

    1. Understand which features are the most representative of the classification
    2. Ensure there is no missing data
    3. Ensure the data set is large enough.
    4. This site is a great resource to find large, publicly available data sets: https://www.dataquest.io/blog/free-datasets-for-projects/

### Setting prize and deadline

1. Within the **Physician** tab, enter an Ether prize (i.e. 100) and a deadline in MM/DD/YYYY (this will be ignored for the demo).
2. Click &#39;Submit Dataset&#39; and select the training set we just downloaded.
3. Below the button you will see the dataset was successfully uploaded to IPFS and that the competition was added to the blockchain.
4. Click on the **Blockchain View** tab to see the _NewCompetition_

### Start the competition

1. We are now ready to host a machine learning competition. On the **Physician** tab click &#39;Initiate Competition Factory.&#39; This will deploy our _CompetitionFactory_ smart contract to our private blockchain running in the background.
2. To see this, click on **Blockchain View** tab to see the blockchain transaction details consisting of the action, the _competitionId_, the actor, the cost of the transaction, and the timestamp.

## View ongoing competitions

1. Click on the **Scientist** tab and view the ongoing competitions
    1. You&#39;ll only see one ongoing competition is ongoing, as today that is the maximum number supported.
2. Click on the &#39;Qmâ€¦&#39; hash URL to view the training dataset for the competition. For this demo, we created R scripts that take in the training set and create a machine learning model.

## Submit a model

1. To ensure you can get started, we have supplied two models to use.  For our application, we ran a decision tree model on the training set (with maximum tree depth of 4 to prevent immense overfitting) and performed classification on the test set. We have reached an approximate 81% in training data, and 75% prediction accuracy on the test set, which can be served as a benchmark for competition.  We compared it to a support vector machine model.   Please download these models from:
    1. [https://github.com/WorldCerebrum/MARIA/blob/master/machine\_learning/models/LinearModelTraining.R?raw=True](https://github.com/WorldCerebrum/MARIA/blob/master/machine\_learning/models/LinearModelTraining.R?raw=True)
    2. [https://github.com/WorldCerebrum/MARIA/blob/master/machine\_learning/models/TreeModelTraining.R?raw=True](https://github.com/WorldCerebrum/MARIA/blob/master/machine\_learning/models/TreeModelTraining.R?raw=True)
2. Within the Scientist tab, click the &#39;Submit Model&#39; button and select the &#39;LinearModelTraining.R&#39; script we just downloaded.
    1. As before, below the button in green text make sure you see the file was added to IPFS and the transaction was successful.
3. Confirm the **Blockchain View** added a _NewSubmission_
4. Click on &#39;Submit Model&#39; again and this time select &#39;TreeModelTraining.R&#39;
5. Next, the Physician should upload to IPFS the Test Set and Outcome data used to evaluate the machine learning models.  Download these two csv files from our GitHub repository:
    1.  [https://github.com/WorldCerebrum/MARIA/blob/master/machine\_learning/datasets/testoutcome.csv?raw=True](https://github.com/WorldCerebrum/MARIA/blob/master/machine\_learning/datasets/testoutcome.csv?raw=True)
    2. [https://github.com/WorldCerebrum/MARIA/blob/master/machine\_learning/datasets/testoutcome.csv?raw=True](https://github.com/WorldCerebrum/MARIA/blob/master/machine\_learning/datasets/testoutcome.csv?raw=True)
6. Navigate back to the **Physician** Tab and click &#39;Submit Test Set&#39; and select &quot;testingset.csv.&quot;
7. Click &#39;Submit Test Outcome&#39; and select &quot;testoutcome.csv.&quot;

## Score a competition

1. Now the Physician can run the submitted machine learning models on iExec, the cloud computing platform that runs on a public blockchain. To do this, the Physician needs to type in the IPFS hash of the machine learning model (shown in the **Blockchain View** tab for _NewSubmission_ events) into the IExec config file.
    1. We pre-configured iExec, so you do not need to type in the hash for the LinearModelTraining.R model.
2. Please see special instructions for the remainder of this workflow.
    1. Note, because we constructed a web app with a front-end UI that interacts with a private Ethereum blockchain and IPFS, while iExec runs on the public Ethereum blockchain and also uses IPFS. The separation between the private and public blockchain is important for anonymity to further remove the possibility of re-identifying patient data. This requires interacting with iExec via a command line interface.
3. Click on the **Leaderboard** tab to see the details of the winner.
4. When the special instructions are run, which presumably would only happen at the end of the deadline for a competition, the model highest in the leaderboard would be automatically awarded a payout.
   1. Due to the constraints, mentioned above, we have a separate workflow for this.  Please see next section, _Payouts_.



### Payouts

1. To pay the scientist that created an ML model with the highest accuracy, copy the address of the scientist contained in stdout.txt (from special instructions) and then paste it into the form above &#39;Execute Payouts&#39;.
2. Click &#39;Execute Payouts&#39; to send the prize to the scientist.
   1. For the purpose of this demo, we hard-coded the scientist address internally so you don&#39;t accidently send Ether to some other account.
3. Click on the **Blockchain View** tab to make sure the transaction occurred.

## FHIR Data Viewer

1. After identifying the winner, Physicians can use MARIA to import their patient&#39;s FHIR data to find patient&#39;s that might benefit from whatever the model is intended to support.
2. Click on **FHIR Viewer** tab to see the dataset we will use for our mock competition.
   1. When the tab is loaded, it connects to _SyntheticMass_ to pull Patient and Observation data.  Data is fetched for patients that have diabetes or pre-diabetes conditions.
3. Scroll down to the bottom left hand corner of the page to download this data. Click on &#39;Export to csv&#39; to save the dataset.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)
    1. Per our approved spec, this data is for a physician to view his or her own patients&#39; data.  Ideally, once a competition has finished and a winning model has been determined, they could use the FHIR data import element of the application to find patient&#39;s they are responsible for who could benefit from the model.
